    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-11-29T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-11-29T06:00:00-05:00" n="284"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d284">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/492: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Perkins</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-11-29T19:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 29, 1929—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 29—7:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1056. Your 394, November 28, noon. Following from American Consul in charge at
                    Mukden: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“November 28, 4 p.m. Reliably informed that Tsai Yun-sheng arrived at
                            Mukden from Vladivostok on the 26th with Soviet terms for the holding of
                            a [conference?] and restoration of power of Soviet manager and immediate
                            release of prisoners.</p>
                        <p>After conference of high officials at Marshal’s<note n="33"
                                xml:id="d284fn33">Chang Hsüeh-liang.</note> villa same day a
                            telegram was sent to Moscow accepting in principle Soviet terms on <pb
                                facs="0507" n="363" xml:id="pg_363"/> condition that terms 1 and 3
                            be first referred to a joint committee to arrange procedure. Old wing of
                                party<note n="34" xml:id="d284fn34">Fengtien Party, formerly led by
                                the late Marshal Chang Tso-lin.</note> responsible for this peace
                            overture. No reply as yet.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
